properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A spring storm, tracking southeastward from Alberta will bring a variety of weather to the prairies over the weekend. The worst conditions are expected to occur over Alberta and southern Saskatchewan where a number of weather warnings are currently in place. Southwestern and extreme southern Manitoba will be clipped by this system. Current indications are that the the precipitation will fall as rain or wet snow over the region and as a result snowfall amounts are expected to be reduced. Nevertheless local accumulations of 5 cm or higher may be possible in some localities especially over the Turtle Mountains. In addition, strong northerly winds gusting to 60 km/h may combine with the falling snow to produce reduced visibilities in blowing snow. The system is expected to exit the region Sunday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A further 2 to 5 cm is expected before the late season snowfall ends tonight. A cold trough which swept through BC today has brought cold air and wintry weather to the mountain passes and in some areas, to valley bottoms. A further 2 to 5 cm is forecast before ending later this evening. Gusty northeasterly winds this afternoon and tonight combined with falling snow could produce periods of blowing snow. Motorists are encouraged to be prepared for winter driving conditions and consult DriveBC for road conditions before travelling. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. A spring storm, tracking southeastward across southern Alberta, will bring an assortment of weather to southern Saskatchewan over the weekend. In general, the worst conditions are expected to occur south of a line stretching from Kindersley to Oxbow. In this area significant wet snowfall is expected with the highest accumulations occurring over the Cypress Hills and Assiniboia areas. Blizzard and Winter Storm warnings are currently in effect for these regions. North of this line, including Regina and the Trans-Canada Highway east to the Manitoba border, snowfall amounts will be significantly less. Amounts near the Trans-Canada Highway may reach 5 cm but fall dramatically as one heads north. The wet nature of the snow will make snowfall amounts highly variable. Despite the lower snowfall amounts, northerly winds in the area will aombine with the falling snow creating poor visibilities in blowing snow overnight into early Sunday morning with visibilities improving by midday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A low pressure system tracking southeastward from southern Alberta will bring heavy wet snow and blowing snow to southwestern Saskatchewan tonight and Sunday. Showers and isolated thunderstorms in the region this evening will transition to snow tonight as strong northerly winds develop over the area. These winds, gusting at times to 80 km/h, will combine with the falling snow resulting in blizzard conditions overnight. Blizzard conditions are expected to improve in the Leader and Gull Lake area in the morning, Swift Current towards midday with the Cypress Hills and Shaunavon areas improving Sunday afternoon. Snow associated with this system will at times be heavy and accumulate rapidly. Storm totals are forecast to be in the 10 to 20 cm range with 30 cm or more possible over the Cypress Hills. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Spring storm continues to give heavy snow and blowing snow to southern Alberta. In the wake of the cold front passing through this evening, expect very strong northerly winds gusting as high as 100 km/h. These strong winds combined with heavy falling snow will lead to reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Localized whiteout conditions are expected, especially in places such as the Highway 2 corridor and sections of the Trans-Canada Highway and Highway 1A near Calgary. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are expected with locally higher amounts near 30 cm possible. Heavy snow and strong winds will taper off from the north overnight and into Sunday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A low pressure system developing in Alberta will track to the southeast and bring snow and blowing snow to southern Saskatchewan tonight through Sunday. Showers with isolated thunderstorms in the area early this evening will transition to snow overnight as strong northerly winds bring colder air to the region. The heaviest snowfall is expected south of a line extending from Kindersley to Oxbow where total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are likely. Snowfall amounts will diminish rapidly north of this line. Strong northerly winds gusting to 70 km/h in combination with falling snow will also cause visibilities to be significantly reduced in blowing snow. Conditions are expected to improve over the Kindersley and Outlook areas Sunday morning with areas to the southeast improving in the afternoon ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. properties.Summary:
Description: A further 2 to 5 cm is expected before the late season snowfall ends tonight. Motorists are encouraged to be prepared for winter driving conditions and consult DriveBC for road conditions before travelling. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Spring storm continues to give heavy snow and blowing snow to southern Alberta. In the wake of the cold front passing through this evening, expect strong northerly winds gusting as high as 80 km/h. These strong winds combined with heavy falling snow will lead to reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Localized whiteout conditions are expected, especially in places such as the Highway 2 corridor and sections of the Trans-Canada Highway and Highway 1A near Calgary. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are expected with locally higher amounts near 30 cm possible. Heavy snow and strong winds will taper off overnight and into Sunday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
